me is also found in Romania, Slovakia, Croatia, and Serbia, and also among Rusyns (in Serbia and Croatia). See also   Pop   2 and   Popa  .","English: variant of   Pape   1."],"variants":[{"name":"Papp","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Hungarian Laszlo, Zoltan, Geza, Istvan, Gabor, Miklos, Tibor, Arpad, Denes, Imre, Attila.","German (Bavaria, Tyrol): from Middle High German <i>pap</i> ‘baby food’, Dutch <i>pap</i> ‘porridge, pap’, hence perhaps a nickname denoting someone who had lost his teeth or subsisted on a meager diet.","Hungarian: from <i>pap</i> ‘priest (of the Catholic or Orthodox Church)’, probably an occupational name for someone in the service of a priest or a nickname for a pious person. This surname is also found in Romania and Slovakia, and also among Rusyns. Compare   Pap   and   Pop  ."]}]},{"name":"Madog","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["French Canadian: variant of   Madore  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Madore","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Eusebe, Fernand, Lucien, Normand, Adhemar, Adrien, Donat, Elzear, Francois, Gaetan, Gilles.","French Canadian: from a French shortened form of the Spanish personal name <i>Amador</i>, from Latin <i>Amator</i> (from <i>amator</i> ‘lover’), a Christian saint's name. Compare   Mador  .","In some cases possibly also Breton (<b>Madoré</b>): nickname meaning literally ‘good help’, from Old Breton <i>mat</i> ‘good’ and <i>uuoret</i> ‘help’."]}]},{"name":"Gwilym","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["equivalent of <b>William</b> , in use since the Middle Ages."],"variants":[{"name":"Gwilim","meanings":["equivalent of <b>William</b> , in use since the Middle Ages."]},{"name":"Gwillym","meanings":["equivalent of <b>William</b> , in use since the Middle Ages."]},{"name":"William","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."]}]},{"name":"Sais","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Fernando, Orlando, Angelita, Arturo, Delfina, Desiderio, Dionicio, Edgardo, Elva, Fidel, Isidoro, Jere.","Catalan: topographic name from <i>saix</i> ‘rock’ (from Latin <i>saxum</i>), or an ethnic name for a Saxon, derived from the root of <i>saxó</i> ‘Saxon’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. Gwilym Sais ap Madog was born about 1257, in Merthyr Tydfil, Wales, United Kingdom. She had at least 4 sons with Gwilym Sais ap Madog."},"et":{"about 1257–Deceased":"umbes 1257–Surnud","1253–Male":"1253–Surnud","1279–Male":"1279–Surnud","1283–Male":"1283–Surnud","1285–Male":"1285–Surnud","1287–1343":"1287–1343","1257–Female":"1257–Surnud","1257":"1257","1279":"1279","1343":"1343","1287":"1287","about 1257":"umbes 1257","1253":"1253","1285":"1285","1283":"1283","Merthyr Tydfil, Wales, United Kingdom":"Merthyr Tydfil, Wales, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1257–Deceased":"noin 1257–Kuollut","1253–Male":"1253–Kuollut","1279–Male":"1279–Kuollut","1283–Male":"1283–Kuollut","1285–Male":"1285–Kuollut","1287–1343":"1287–1343","1257–Female":"1257–Kuollut","1257":"1257","1279":"1279","1343":"1343","1287":"1287","about 1257":"noin 1257","1253":"1253","1285":"1285","1283":"1283","Merthyr Tydfil, Wales, United Kingdom":"Merthyr Tydfil, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuning